{'title': 'A brief introduction to Oracle Extractable Value(OEV)', 'description': 'Oracle Extractable Value (OEV) is a specific type of Maximal Extractable Value (MEV) that creates opportunities for value capture by exploiting inconsistencies between on-chain and off-chain data. The data provided by oracles often lags behind the real-world market prices, thus when oracles update their data, experienced participants—including searchers, block builders, and proposers (Validators)—can find profitable opportunities.

This mechanism involves not only front-running but also cross-platform arbitrage and liquidation of collateral to obtain rewards.

Currently, projects related to OEV aim to address the issue of unfair distribution of value, allowing protocols and applications to capture these profits and redistribute them. These projects reduce hidden costs extracted by third parties from blockchain transactions through OFA, thereby enhancing the revenue of dApps and improving user experience.'}

